The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganize the working days, the number of which will decrease next year.
Holidays are not uniform in the EU and the United States either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes between national and state holiday days and days of rest.
Days of rest are often linked to religious festivals or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the New Year are also days of rest, all the more so that New Year's Eve can rest quietly.
Moreover, in a year, we have a total of eleven festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, in commemoration of the revolution of 1848, as is October 23 which is also the commemorative day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20th, we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1st is Labour Day and on November 1st and 2nd, we remember our deceased family members and friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
The days of our state holidays, national or even religious rarely falling on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize working days in cases where there is only one working day before or after the feast marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price for extended weekends by working or going to school the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has ruled in a special regulation on the replacement days of the days preceding or following the holidays.
The Act covers all employers and their employees, civil servants and persons working in the public service.
It does not, however, apply to service companies, institutions running continuously and in service, because of their vocation, and also for days of rest.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from 24 December, life ends almost all over the country because according to experiences the majority of people do more overtime or take holidays that they have saved for these purposes so that they can spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized for the first time around the Labour Day to allow employees to stay at home four days in a row.
Saturday, April 25, will be a working day to have a day of rest on Friday, May 2.
Another change is scheduled for October 23rd: Saturday, October 18th will be a working day to replace Friday 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year will be marked by holidays because from 24 December, everyone will take a non-stop break even if the New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
