Better than we expected
This follows on from the government's strategy for financing and managing the government's 2007 debt, which the government planned to borrow 159.2 billion kroner this year.
However, in early September, thanks to better-than-expected changes in the state budget savings, the Ministry reduced the planned amount to DKr 152.8 billion.
The sum consists mainly of the deficit in the State budget, which is clearly going to reach SEK 76 billion this year, instead of the SEK 91.3 billion originally planned.
Secondly, the maximum sources foreseen for the Czech consolidation agency are 13.3 billion kroons, the reserve of 10 billion for the payment of pensions, the financing of state pension securities for 43 billion kroons and repayments of loans from the European Investment Bank amounting to 1.8 billion kroons.
She was appearing today before a court in Khartoum for appointing a teddy bear
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday evening by a court in Khartoum to 15 days in prison and to deportation, said her lawyer.
The British woman was accused of having left pupils between the ages of 6 and 7 to give the name of Muhammad to a teddy bear while any representation of the prophet of Islam was illegal.
She was liable to a penalty of whipping.
This 54-year-old British teacher at the Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested Sunday at her home and charged with violating Islam and sedition, under article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints from parents of students to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story goes back in fact to September, when this teacher asks her students, aged 6/7, to choose a name for the teddy bear of the class.
"Eight names come out of the mouths of children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed," says school principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred name.
Mohamed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the bear's photo followed by the legend "My name is Mohamed".
The bear itself did not bear any label with this name, but the problem is simply that of representing the prophet as an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said that he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that could be insulting to a religious faith, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name," he says it is only an "innocent mistake."
Opinion shared by many of the teacher's students who describe her as "very attentive to her students" and "who never speaks of religion in the classroom".
Recall that the first name Mohamed is also the second name most given in Great Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way to honor the prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
Can we give it to a toy, for example?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
On Wednesday, they did not reach an agreement on the future status of the province at the last negotiating session in Vienna.
In the end, failure.
Kosovo Serbs and Albanians completed a sixth and final session of discussions on Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without having been able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on the Statute," said European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger at a press conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was “at stake”, his American counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to honour their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
"We do not expect violence in the immediate future, but we are entering a very difficult period," he added, noting that "obvious tensions exist".
End of mediation on 10 December
The ombudsmen of the troika, which brings together the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The future of the 90% Albanian-speaking province could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and the Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Kharchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by 10 December.
The discussions in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and last session of negotiations since the troika was entrusted with a new mediation by the United Nations last August.
Americans and Europeans consider that their mediation will end on 10 December.
The Russians, who have already blocked the granting of independence to Kosovo in the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond that deadline.
"Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution," said Botsane-Kharchenko.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
After eight years of UN administration in Kosovo, Westerners believe that EU-supervised independence is the only viable solution.
Pristina expresses its readiness to declare it unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in its favour.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," announced the president of the Kosovo Autonomous Authority, Fatmir Sejdiu, in the Baden hotel where these "last chance negotiations" have been taking place since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future premier of the province, expressed his regret.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belongs to a past that led to murders and deportations".
‘Domino effect’
Serbian President Boris Tadic, for his part, considered that a compromise was always possible, warning the Albanian majority in Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the independence of the province.
In particular, Belgrade said it feared a "domino effect" in a region still weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
"For Serbia," he said, "this does not mean that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision should be taken exclusively by the Security Council, where its Russian ally has the right of veto.
"The Kosovo Parliament will have the last word"
"Only one solution in the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia," said Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica.
“These negotiations lasted two years.
They must end as they have begun: in the Security Council.”
To the journalists, Fatmir Sedjiu replied that "the Kosovo Parliament will have the final say on the status", adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanian-speaking people would be "in consultation" with the Westerners.
