This name covers the three thorny problems at the heart of the dispute between Israelis and Palestinians: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of Arab refugees driven out of their homes in what is today the State of Israel during the 1948 conflict.
Speaking after the US President, Abbas insisted that future negotiations be "global and thorough" and address all aspects of a settlement, citing "Jerusalem, refugees, borders, settlements, water, security, among others."
Going up to the podium, Olmert pledged that the upcoming talks would be "direct and continuous" and to make "an effort to close them in the course of 2008".
Bush set at the end of 2008 the deadline for the implementation of his "vision of two states" Palestinian and Israeli co-existing.
Saudi Arabia revealed that it had obtained a commitment to this from Bush before deciding to participate in the conference.
