It took more than seven hours of space work for astronaut Scott Parazynski and his fellow crew of the International Space Station (ISS) to perform the spectacular repair of a torn solar panel, essential to the continuation of the station's scientific activities.
A risky exit that has accumulated the records because of its duration, its remoteness from the habitable modules, the speed with which it was conceived, the tools "doed" by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem arose on Tuesday when the astronauts had unloaded the Harmony module, a large cylindrical room that would soon house the European and Japanese scientific laboratories (see box).
This module is a kind of dock for laboratory modules.
But we must be able to supply them with electricity.
The crew's second task, therefore, was to move a solar power generation module weighing 17.5 tonnes, already present on the ISS, to position it in its final position.
After moving it, the crew began the redeployment of the module's solar panels, which have a wingspan of 76 metres.
And that's where one of the panels, which unfold like accordions, was damaged on nearly a meter by a cable that got stuck.
The deployment was stopped so as not to further damage the panel.
The astronauts, who were originally required to perform a control exit from the Shuttle Discovery and then to repair another solar panel with a defective rotation system, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged panel.
And it was Scott Parazynski who was chosen to caracole at the end of the 30 meters of length of the remote control arm of the shuttle added to that of the station to perform the repair.
It is one of the best spacewalker in Nasa.
Large, resistant, very skillful, it has a very developed torso and long arms.
At 46 years of age, this trained physician was charged with "operating" the "injured" solar panel.
After precisely inspecting the damage, he severed the faulty cable and installed some kind of "clamps" on the damaged area.
He was assisted by a second "spacewalker" who remained near the airlock and, from the inside, by other astronauts, including Peggy Whitson, the crew commander.
The tool he used, a hockey mini-cane wrapped in insulation to avoid electrocution on solar panels producing hundreds of volts, was designed and "bricoled" by astronauts aboard the station.
Once the operation was complete, Scott Parazynski waited until the panel was fully deployed before making an inventory of his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation before today, seven astronauts returned to the Shuttle Discovery for a return to Earth scheduled for Wednesday.
