The Harmonised Index of Consumer Prices increased by five-tenths in November, up to 4.1%.
This indicator, which is then used by Eurostat to incorporate it into the calculation of the rate of inflation in the European Union, provides a balance sheet on the price developments in Spain during the month of November.
Its publication responds to the policy of Eurostat and the European Central Bank (ECB) by offering data comparable in time and quality to those produced in the United States.
The advanced indicator is calculated using the same process used for the Harmonized Consumer Price Index, but using various statistical modelling methods to estimate the information that is not yet available for publication.
The INE recalled that the information provided by the leading indicator is indicative only, because it does not necessarily coincide with the final data that will be released on December 14.
"The CPI will continue at relatively high levels"
The second vice-president and the minister of the economy, Pedro Solbes, said that the 4.1% increase in the CPI in November is a "time figure", but at the same time he predicted that the price index will continue on "relatively high" levels in the coming months.
In any case Solbes stated in the Congressional corridors that "although the figure is not good" Spain's inflation differential with regard to monetary union continues to be "more or less" the same as in recent years.
