The Scottish Ministry of Health needs to improve the checks to be carried out on its extra-community employees to check whether they have criminal precedents, the Monitoring Committee said.
Reviser General Robert Black's warning came after a foreign doctor working in Scotland was involved in the attack at Glasgow airport in June.
Mr Black also expressed concern that the Scottish Ministry of Health has no precise data on the number of overseas workers he employs.
His report nevertheless highlighted other decisive checks, correctly carried out on a sample of employees from five health authorities.
The Auditor General conducted checks on extra-Community personnel following the attack on Glasgow airport.
