The Ministry of Health will have to carry out pre-employment checks on overseas staff, to be sure of the validity of their qualifications, experiences, and work permits for the United Kingdom.
Although the Scottish Ministry of Health uses the Scottish Disclosure to carry out checks on criminal precedents, the Agency has no right to obtain such information outside of Great Britain.
Among the many warnings, the Auditor General's report now states that committees are required to confront the Office of Control of Criminal Precedents, thus allowing employers to undertake controls over various countries.
"Although we have discovered that some personnel information has been verified, this is not done every time," the report says.
Mr Black stated that the Scottish Ministry of Health carries out most of the pre-employment checks he would do himself, but he also added: "Our report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure that adequate information on certain overseas staff is available to health services.
Mr Peter Terry, President of BMA Scotland said that it is "extremely unlikely" that pre-employment checks can identify employees likely to commit future terrorist acts.
