The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a subsidiary of the PLC group of the Royal Bank of Scotland, have become famous throughout Great Britain because of the two-year extradition procedures.
In the United States, their case remains a pending issue for this investigation launched following the fall of Enron in 2001.
The charges laid against them in 2002 made Fastow understand that he was the subject of the government's investigation into the Enron debacle.
The accusations against the bankers, nicknamed "Natwest's Three", claim to have come to Houston in 2000 to organize a fraudulent scenario with Fastow and his ex-right-hand Michael Kopper.
