At the beginning of 2002, the bank had estimated its interest in the subsidiary as null, but in fact the three British already know its value.
A company controlled by Kopper bought the interest of the subsidiary bank for £1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 as interest for this company.
According to the accused, Fastow falsely announced to Enron that the energy company was willing to pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its shares in the subsidiary.
But the truth is that $20 million went into the pockets of British bankers, Fastow and others.
According to the accusations, the bankers would have gotten $7.3 while Fastow, Kopper and the others would have earned $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to his active role in two conspiracies in the Enron debacle.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year prison term in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is incarcerated for three years and a month in a prison in Texarkana.
The three British were released on bail of $1 million each, forcing them to live in the United States during the trial.
