Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere hostile to life, Venus looks more like the Earth than we thought so far: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind whirlwinds at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightnings on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" has today provided proof of this - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: the lightnings on Venus burst at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of cyprine, lightning would have revealed life on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If life has been there, it must have been at a very old time in history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be few living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the infernal twin of the Earth, but she's still a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like the Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venetian research, since no probe had been on its way to explore this planet since the 1990s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent results of research that have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" do not only emphasize the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the commonalities with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than supposed at first sight.
Thus the researchers found, in addition to the wind whirlwinds already known at the North Pole, a cloud whirlwind at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon recalls the currents of air in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica Italian.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet described as an evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much more slowly on itself: a Venetian day lasts 243 earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly reminds the Earth, scientists assume that the two planets were formed under similar conditions.
On both, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth in the form of carbonate, it constitutes most of the atmosphere on Venus.
