They're not Warhols' crates.
The one who connects Swedish concepts and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Stockholm Type" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today results in a disillusioning result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", whose former director of the Pontus Hulten museum donated in 1995 to the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as a large part of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Stockholm Type", which circulate on the international art market.
Ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting sequence of artistic and curatorical productions.
In 1964, Warhol created its first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, based on the red-blue-white design of the powder soap cartons "Brillo".
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo carpentry factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had indeed given permission in 1968 to produce a few wooden boxes in Brillo in Sweden, which were not, moreover, exposed to the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden crates that at the time would have entered by right into the history of art and auction, as the original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the name "Stockholm Type".
Some of them have reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hulten museum falsely claimed, later, that about 100 wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have given to him.
In fact, Hulten's 105 crates were produced in Malmö in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminate panels were first printed and sanded, and then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The texture of the copies dating back to 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was applied directly without a background layer on the laminate panels, using a roll of paint - moreover, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These crates have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
Already in July the Authentication Board announced, of course, that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap crates.
But since then, we've been lulled there with an inexorable silence.
The Rebel Soldiers of Manila Abandon
In the Philippines, the rebel soldiers abandoned, the same ones who had cut themselves off in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blamed the President for corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters in the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
The soldiers loyal to the power had shortly before stormed the hotel with tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been in the building for hours.
About half of them were held in court on Wednesday due to a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly slip away with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who normally had to monitor them, had apparently deserted in his favour and had joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
The troops loyal to the government completed the area around the respectable hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
"People have had enough," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to join us."
General Danilo Lim, who was in command before the Scout Ranger elite unit, said that other army units soon wanted to join the march.
Critics of the regime had called for a major demonstration against the President on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
Since 2003, Manila's finance district has been the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo.
The insurrection broke almost 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986 there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
